WEEK 7 

1.Introduction

In this Week , the focus of the project was on applying advanced analytical concepts using DAX (Data Analysis Expressions), creating measures, designing visuals, and building interactive dashboards in Power BI.
After completing data modelling in the previous stage, the dataset was ready for analysis. This stage involved transforming structured data into meaningful insights through calculations and visual representations

2.Introduction to DAX

DAX (Data Analysis Expressions) is a formula language used in Power BI for creating custom calculations. It helps in deriving new insights from existing data and plays a crucial role in building dynamic dashboards.
Uses of DAX:
•	Creating calculated columns
•	Creating measures
•	Performing aggregations (SUM, COUNT, AVERAGE)
•	Applying filters and logical conditions
DAX enables flexible and powerful data analysis in Power BI.

3.Measures in Power BI

Measures are dynamic calculations created using DAX that change based on the context of the visual. They are used to analyze data and display results in charts, tables, and KPI cards.
Example:
Average Resolution Time = AVERAGE(Table[Resolution Time])
Measures are essential for calculating key performance indicators.

4.Types of Measures

4.1 Implicit Measures
Implicit measures are automatically generated by Power BI when a field is added to a visual.
Characteristics:
•	No manual formula required
•	Default aggregations (SUM, COUNT, etc.)
•	Easy to use but limited flexibility
•	
4.2 Explicit Measures
Explicit measures are manually created using DAX formulas.
Characteristics:
•	Provides full control over calculations
•	Reusable across multiple visuals
•	Supports complex logic

5. Base Measure and Composite Measure

5.1 Base Measure
A base measure is a simple calculation created directly from dataset columns.
Example:
Total Tickets = COUNT(Ticket ID)
It acts as a foundation for further calculations.

5.2 Composite Measure
A composite measure is created by combining multiple base measures.
Example:
SLA Compliance % = (Tickets Met SLA / Total Tickets) * 100
Composite measures provide deeper insights and support advanced analysis.

6. Importance of Relationships Between Visuals

Relationships between tables ensure that visuals in Power BI interact correctly with each other.
Importance:
•	Enables cross-filtering between visuals
•	Maintains data consistency
•	Supports accurate calculations
•	Improves interactivity
Example:
Selecting a specific agent in one chart will automatically filter data in other visuals if relationships are properly defined.
Without relationships, visuals will not communicate, and analysis will be incorrect.

7. Working with Visuals

Visuals are graphical representations of data that help users understand patterns and trends.
Common Visuals Used:
•	Bar Chart → Category comparison
•	Pie Chart → Distribution analysis
•	Line Chart → Trend over time
•	Table → Detailed data view
•	Card → KPI display
Visuals make data easier to interpret and support decision-making.

8. Slicers in Power BI

Slicers are interactive filters that allow users to control the data displayed in visuals.
Features:
•	Dynamic filtering
•	Easy user interaction
•	Improves dashboard usability
Example:
•	Filter by Priority
•	Filter by Agent Name
•	Filter by Country
Slicers enhance the interactivity of dashboards.

9. Dashboard Creation

Dashboards were created to present insights in a structured and user-friendly manner.

9.1 Number of Dashboards Created
In this project, three dashboards (report pages) were created:
1.	Overview Dashboard
2.	Performance Dashboard
3.	Analysis Dashboard

9.2 Dashboard Titles
•	IT Support Ticket Overview Dashboard
•	Support Team Performance Dashboard
•	Ticket Analysis and Insights Dashboard

9.3 Basic Structure of Dashboard
Each dashboard was designed with a consistent layout:
Top Section:
•	KPI Cards (Total Tickets, Avg Resolution Time, SLA %)
Middle Section:
•	Charts (Priority distribution, Agent performance)
Bottom Section:
•	Detailed insights (Country, Ticket type)
Side Section:
•	Slicers for filtering

9.4 Steps to Create Dashboard
1.	Open Power BI → Report View
2.	Create new pages for each dashboard
3.	Add KPI cards using measures
4.	Insert charts and visuals
5.	Drag and drop required fields
6.	Add slicers for filtering
7.	Format visuals (titles, colors, labels)
8.	Arrange visuals properly

10. Design Considerations

While creating dashboards, the following were considered:
•	Clear and meaningful titles
•	Proper alignment of visuals
•	Consistent color theme
•	Avoid overcrowding
•	Easy navigation

11. Outcome of Week 7

By the end of Week :
•	DAX formulas were implemented
•	Measures were created and used
•	Visuals and slicers were designed
•	Dashboards were created with proper structure
•	Interactive analysis was achieved

Summary
In this Week , DAX and measures were used to perform advanced data analysis. Visuals and slicers were implemented to create interactive dashboards. Relationships ensured proper data flow between visuals.
This stage transformed the dataset into meaningful insights and resulted in the creation of structured and user-friendly dashboards.
